<p>Cyclopentadiene is a fairly common reagent in both organic and organometallic synthesis, however its use is complicated by its facile dimerization into dicyclopentadiene <em>via</em> a Diels-Alder cycloaddition.</p>

<center>
    <img src="/assets/cpdimer.png" width="396" height="77.9" />
</center>

<p>Your PI Prof. Batman and his lab manager Dr. Robin ask if you could use your newfound computational skills to study this reaction. In particular, they’d like to know:</p>

<ul>
  <li>The relative energies of the <em>exo-</em> and <em>endo-</em>dicyclopentadiene isomers,</li>
  <li>The free energy of dimerization (ΔG<sub>rxn</sub>), and</li>
  <li>The <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thermodynamic_versus_kinetic_reaction_control">kinetic product</a><sup>1</sup> of the reaction (unless you’ve done completed the Long Course you won’t be able to do this one just yet)</li>
</ul>

<p>See if you can do this one yourself!<br />
Check your work with the solution in the <a href="https://github.com/thisisntnathan/dftShortCourseFiles">code repo</a> or literature values.<sup>2,3,4</sup></p>

